      "content": "Look, I hear you on the risk, but I've been through this before. Sometimes these automated scanners flag things that are technically \"critical\" in a sandbox or against dummy data, but in our actual production environment, the WAF (Web Application Firewall) is already tuned to catch this specific pattern. \n\nThe WAF has a rule active for 'SQLi-Pattern-Alpha' that should drop these requests before they even hit the legacy API. If we take the portal down now, we're looking at millions in lost revenue and a massive hit to our SLA. If I can tell the board that the current risk is actually mitigated by the WAF and we can just monitor it until the scheduled downtime, would that be an accurate assessment of the situation? I'm just trying to figure out if the \"Critical\" label is being a bit hyperbolic given our layers of defense.",
